<TEXT>
a federal judge has dismissed payola charges 
against a san franciscoarea record promoter saying the counts in 
the muchpublicized justice department investigation were too vague 
us district judge pamela rymer in response to a defense 
motion on friday dismissed three misdemeanor payola counts against 
ralph tashjian of san mateo on the grounds the grand jury 
indictment wasnt specific enough to allow the promoter to defend 
himself 
court documents showed tashjian was charged with making regular 
undisclosed payments or distributions of cocaine to program 
directors so the records he was promoting would be added to radio 
station play lists 
prosecutor richard stavin a special attorney for the los angeles 
organized crime strike force said the government next week plans to 
charge tashjian with 200 individual counts of payola 
stavin attributed the dismissal to a weakness in the payola 
statute that addresses only specific incidents and doesnt 
contemplate a scheme or ongoing course of action 
tashjian and his wife are set to stand trial later this month on 
separate felony tax evasion charges stemming from the payola case 
reacting to the judges ruling tashjians attorney anthony p 
brooklier said the problem was the government charged my client 
with multiple offenses over a long period of time without specifying 
the dates of those alleged offenses or the records involved 
the tashjians along with another record promoter and a former 
radio station manager were indicted in february 1988 after the 
internal revenue service conducted a twoyear investigation under 
the direction of the organized crime strike force charges against 
the other defendants were pending 
</TEXT>
