<TEXT>
major american steel companies are spending 
millions of dollars to try to document alleged unfair trading 
practices by leading steelexporting nations 
the move is part of a campaign by the american steel industry to 
win an extension of a series of pacts that set productbyproduct 
limits on the amount of foreign steel that can be shipped into the 
united states 
the pacts were negotiated by the reagan administration with 
japan south korea brazil and other nations in 1984 in response to 
complaints by american steelmakers that they could not compete with 
a flood of subsidized foreign imports 
the agreements expire sept 30 and usx corp bethlehem steel 
corp and other leading steelmakers want to be certain they are 
renewed the bush administration has pledged to support the pacts 
although no specifics have been offered on whether they would be 
continued in their present form 
the wild cards in the negotiations will be the nations 
themselves they are under no obligation to restrict their imports 
again as they did voluntarily five years ago 
in order to pressure the trading partners american steelmakers 
have been paying millions of dollars to lawyers to compile unfair 
trading cases against the countries according to usx and 
bethlehem executives 
in the cases the lawyers are detailing allegations of foreign 
government subsidies to steelmakers and dumping or selling 
products in the united states at below fairmarket value 
the unfair trading cases may never actually be filed with the 
us international trade commission an independent agency with 
authority to order tariffs or other import relief for injured 
domestic industries 
but the american companies are compiling the cases anyway so the 
united states can use the information as leverage in negotiations 
trade cases are an alternative an expensive undesirable 
alternative robert boni chief executive officer of armco inc 
said in a recent interview 
while steel industry officials are reluctant to publicly discuss 
the specifics of such cases boni said armco of parsippany nj 
spent 2 million recently just on lawyers who are compiling them he 
said larger steelmakers probably were spending more 
under the fiveyear trade pacts imports have been reduced from 
264 percent of the american steel market in 1984 to about 205 
percent last year meanwhile employment levels and profit among 
us steelmakers were up last year over 1987 
while us steelmakers say they continue to need the protection 
of import curbs some other american manufacturers contend the 
restraints have created steel shortages in the united states and 
driven up prices 
</TEXT>
